result.execSummary:
The defendant Choua Xiong was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Neglecting a Child (Consequence is Great Bodily Harm), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(1)(c).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

As such, Stephan Xiong shall be an exception to the no-contact provision. **

Defendant Choua Xiong in court with attorney Michael Daniel Zell. Defendant Choua Xiong in custody. Louis J. Molepske appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Matter is scheduled for a sentencing hearing today. Defendant previously entered a plea. Court ordered a PSI, one was prepared and copies were forwarded to counsel.
Victim was given notification. Victim is present and has prepared two victim impact statements.
Atty Molepske has no corrections or additions with regards to the PSI.
Atty Zell has no corrections or additions with regards to the PSI, only statements that will be addressed later.

10:26 AM Court has been presented with copies of the impact statements and reads them quietly at this time.

State requests that the victim's statements be read out loud, per request of the victim.
Court reads the statements out loud, for the record.

Atty Zell has provided the doctor document as well as the safety plan to the Court.

Court takes a moment to read the safety plan. 

There will be no testimony presented.

Atty Molepske addresses the Court prior to sentencing.
State requests a withheld sentence, 7 yrs probation, costs, no less than 1 yr jail and conditions outlined.

Atty Zell addresses the Court prior to sentencing, concurs with probation but objects the length of jail.
Length of jail is discussed by all parties.

Defendant addresses the Court prior to sentencing. Atty Zell reads the statement on behalf of his client.
Atty Zell state there is jail credit and requests 3 years probation.

State concurs there is 197 days credit.

Court has a number of factors to consider to determine sentencing.

BY THE COURT:
Sentence is Withheld

Complete a Cognitive Intervention Program (CGIP)

Pay court costs

Do not possess/consume controlled substances without a valid prescription  and be taken according to the prescription

Parties will keep their copy of the PSI, will keep them confidential.
Appeal rights are addressed.

Defendant Choua Xiong in court with attorney Michael D. Zell. Defendant Choua Xiong in custody. Veronica Isherwood appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Oral Motion regarding bond modification.
Atty Zell makes bond arguments in support of the motion to modify bond for the reasons stated on the record.  Requests to lower the cash bond to $3,000 cash. 
Atty Isherwood makes bond arguments in opposition to the motion to modify bond.  Asks that the bond continue.
Court questions childrens status. 
Atty Zell makes additional arguments to the Court.  Requests supervised visitation. 
Atty Isherwood makes additional arguments to the Court.  Opposes supervised visitation at this time.  

BY THE COURT: 
Court heard the initial presentation of the facts at the riverside hearing.  Court has reviewed the complaint as well.  Court felt at that time and continues to feel these are serious charges with significant penalties if convicted and the terms of the weight of the evidence.  Court understands defense will have their when if and when they hire there own expert.  The doctor from the Marshfield Clinic has her opinion and also there is the statement made by the defendant to the detective as to how the injuries occurred to the child.  Purpose of bond is to assure future court appearance as well as comply with bond conditions.  The infant has sustained significant injury.  Extent of the damange is not known at this time.  Court has not heard new information other than an expert may be able to provide information that would mitigate the strength of the state's case.  As far as the Court is concerned, that is just speculation at this time.  Request to modify the bond is denied.
